- if current_user

  #{puts @hat.class}
  p#title == @hat.title

  p.subtitle Pattern Description
  p
    |
      Unisex hat with negative ease along the brim, and a slight slouch to the body (nothing too hipstery). Optional instructions are provided for a regular beanie or a slouchy cap.

  p.subtitle Very Important
  p
    |
      This pattern generator <i>does not</i> verify if you have enough yardage to complete the pattern at your given gauge. Always double check your yarn quantity against the yarn requirement estimate below before diving in! Read the <a href="/technical">pattern notes</a> for more information.

  h3 Finished size
  p
    |
      #{@hat.size} inches finished circumference (#{@hat.ease} inch brim circumference with negative ease).

  h3 Needles
  ul
    li #{@hat.needle} 16" circular needle
    li #{@hat.smaller_needle} 16" circular needle (for ribbing)

  h3 Gauge
  p
    |
      #{@hat.per_4} stitches per 4 inches/10 cms, #{@hat.row_4} rows per 4 inches/10 cms.

  h3 Yarn information
  p
    |
      #{@hat.yarn_brand} in #{@hat.yarn_color} (#{@hat.yarn_weight}), approximately #{@hat.yarn_yards} yards/#{@hat.to_meters(@hat.yarn_yards)} meters.

  h3 Estimated yardage
  p
    |
      My big computer brain calculates that you'll need #{@hat.estimated_yardage} yards/#{@hat.to_meters(@hat.estimated_yardage)} meters of #{@hat.yarn_weight} weight yarn to complete this project.
  p.emphasis
    |
      These are estimates based on your gauge and selected yarn weight. It includes approximately 10% wiggle room.

  h3 Abbreviations
  ul.abbreviations
    == @hat.print_abbreviations

  h3 Instructions

  p.subtitle Set Up
  p
    |
      Using #{@hat.smaller_needle}, loosely CO #{@hat.cast_on} sts. PM and join for knitting in the round. Work in #{@hat.ribbing} ribbing for #{@hat.ribbing_rows}. Switch to #{@hat.needle}.

  p For regular hats, proceed to hat body.
  p For a slouchy hat or a beanie, work the increases or decreases listed below before proceeding to hat body.

  p.optionalsubtitle Increases, slouchy hat: increase evenly to #{@hat.slouch} sts. Proceed to hat body.

  p.optionalsubtitle Decreases, beanie: decrease evenly to #{@hat.beanie} sts. Proceed to hat body.

  p.subtitle Hat Body
  p
    |
      Work in the round in your desired stitch motif for appromxiately #{@hat.body_height}.



  p.subtitle Crown Decreases

  p.optionalsubtitle Crown Decreases, slouchy hats
  p
    |
      Work first decrease row as: * k#{@hat.slouch_first_decrease}, k2tog, rpt from * to end.<br>
      Next decrease row: * k#{@hat.slouch_first_decrease-1}, k2tog, rpt from * to end.<br>
      Continue in this manner until you have #{@hat.cast_on} sts. Begin working from the regular crown decrease instructions (below). You may need to adjust the numbers slightly.

  p.optionalsubtitle Crown Decreases, beanies
  p
    |
      Work the regular crown decrease instructions (below), beginning with the row that starts with k#{@hat.beanie_first_decrease}. You may need to adjust the numbers slightly.

  p.optionalsubtitle Crown Decreases, regular hats
  == @hat.crown_decreases



  p
    |
      Cinch remaining sts together. Weave in ends and block if desired.


- else
  p#title Whoops!
  p
    |
      It doesn't look like this is your pattern.
